By David Bardsley

Construction dewatering is the process of removing groundwater from a construction site to provide a safe and stable subgrade for excavation.

Groundwater is removed from the site using deep wells, wellpoints, eductors, or conventional “sump and pump” methods. Dewatering may be temporary during construction activities or permanent for the life of the facility.

// ** Advertisement ** //

Safety is imperative at construction sites, employees don’t like operating with wet feet; this includes workers in excavations, pipeline welders and any other worker at the construction site. Also keeping the bottom of the excavation dry reduces the potential for slipping and tripping hazards and can prevent equipment damage. If the groundwater at the site is contaminated with chemicals from a dry cleaner or a leaking fuel storage tank, removing the water from the site reduces employee exposure to the toxins.

A stable work site is important. Proper removal of the groundwater before construction begins can eliminate excavation failures due to uncontrolled water entering the job site.

